Running this repository on Linux (or macOS) is highly native since you will be using a standard bash or zsh terminal.

Here is the exact, step-by-step process to clone, configure, and run the AI-Lastic-Repository on your Linux machine.

1. Clone the Repository
Open your terminal and download the project to your local machine using Git.

Bash
git clone https://github.com/rushyaayt/AI-Lastic-Repository.git
2. Navigate to the Project Folder
Move inside the directory you just cloned.

Bash
cd AI-Lastic-Repository
3. Install the Dependencies
Ensure you have Python 3 installed on your Linux distribution. Run the following command to install the required libraries. Depending on your setup, you might need to use pip3 instead of pip.

Bash
pip3 install google-genai pydantic pygithub
(Note: If your system restricts global pip installs, you can create a virtual environment first by running python3 -m venv venv and activating it with source venv/bin/activate).

4. Set Your API Keys (Environment Variables)
In Linux terminals, you use the export command to set environment variables for your current session.

Replace the placeholder text with your actual keys:

Bash
export GEMINI_API_KEY="your_actual_gemini_api_key_here"
export GITHUB_TOKEN="your_actual_github_personal_access_token_here"
5. Run the AI Architect
Now that your environment is configured with the necessary credentials, execute the Python script:

Bash
python3 ai_repo_builder.py
Once the script starts, you can type your project prompt directly into the terminal, and the AI will begin building your repository on GitHub.
